{{Infobox criminal | name = John Huang | birth_date = 1945 | birth_place = [[Nanping]], [[Fujian]], [[Republic of China]] | citizenship = [[United States]] | alma_mater = [[University of Connecticut School of Business]] | known_for = Felony conviction | apprehended = August 12, 1999 | module = {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes | office = [[Deputy Assistant Secretary for International Economic Affairs]] | term_start = | term_end = | president = [[Bill Clinton]] }} }} '''John Huang''' ({{zh|c=黄建南}}, born 1945) is a major figure in the [[1996 United States campaign finance controversy]]. He worked for [[Lippo Bank]] in [[California]] and [[Worthen Bank]] in [[Arkansas]], and as deputy assistant secretary for international economic affairs in U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]]'s [[United States Commerce Department|Commerce Department]] before he became a chief fundraiser for the [[Democratic National Committee]] in 1996.<ref name=riady>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/campfin/players/huang.htm "Campaign Finance Key Player: John Huang"], ''Washington Post'', July 27, 1997</ref><ref> *[http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1997/gen/resources/infocus/fundraising.flap/time9610.html "The Democratic Fund-Raising Flap: Timeline"], ''CNN.com'', July 1, 1997 *Duffy, Brian, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/campfin/stories/huang0513.htm "A Fund-Raiser's Rise and Fall"], ''Washington Post'', May 13, 1997</ref>
On August 12, 1999, Huang pleaded guilty to a felony [[Conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] charge for violating campaign finance laws and was sentenced to one year of [[probation]]. He was also ordered by [[U.S. District Court]] to pay a $10,000 fine and serve 500 hours of community service. Prosecutors said Huang was responsible for arranging about $156,000 in illegal campaign contributions from [[Lippo Group]] employees to the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=huangfelon>[http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/08/12/huang.sentence/ "Former Democratic fund-raiser John Huang pleads guilty"], ''CNN.com'', Aug. 12 1999</ref>
Huang was born in 1945 at [[Nanping]] in [[Fujian]]. His father [[Huang Tizhai]] was a native from [[Wenzhou]], [[Zhejiang]] and served the [[KMT]]. Huang and his father fled to [[Taiwan]] at the end of the [[Chinese Civil War]] before he eventually emigrated to the United States in 1969<ref name="riady"/> to study for an [[M.B.A.]] at the [[University of Connecticut]]. After working as a loan officer at small banks around [[Washington D.C.]], Huang moved to [[Kentucky]] and [[Tennessee]] before becoming Vice President of Worthen Bank in Little Rock in 1984. He continued to work for Lippo at the same time.<ref name=cashcow>Greenwald, John, [http://www-cgi.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1996/analysis/time/9611/11/greenwald.shtml "John Huang: The Dems Cash Cow"], ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'', November 11, 1996</ref>
